Installing a Python Library in Google Colab
Open Google Colab: Go to Google Colab and create a new notebook.

Install the Library: In a code cell, install a Python library (e.g., Pandas) using pip.

!pip install pandas


Demonstrate Usage of the Library: Write code to demonstrate the usage of the installed library. For example, create a simple DataFrame and perform a basic operation.

import pandas as pd

# Create a simple DataFrame
data = {'Name': ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Charlie', 'David'],
        'Age': [24, 27, 22, 32],
        'City': ['New York', 'Los Angeles', 'Chicago', 'Houston']}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Display the DataFrame
print("DataFrame:")
print(df)

# Perform a basic operation: calculate the mean age
mean_age = df['Age'].mean()
print("\nMean Age:", mean_age)

Inviting a Collaborator

Invite Collaborator: Click on the "Share" button at the top right corner of the Colab interface.
Enter Email Address: Enter the email address of your classmate or friend (e.g., classmate@example.com) and set the permission to "Can edit".
Send Invitation: Click the "Send" button to invite them to collaborate on your notebook.
Collaborative Task
Collaborate on a Task: Work together on a simple Python code project or data analysis task. For example, you could analyze a dataset or create a plot.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Plot the ages of individuals
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.bar(df['Name'], df['Age'], color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Name')
plt.ylabel('Age')
plt.title('Age of Individuals')
plt.show()

Save and Share Your Notebook
Save to Google Drive: Click on "File" > "Save a copy in Drive" to save the notebook to your Google Drive.
Share the Notebook: Click on the "Share" button again, and enter the email address of your instructor or peer to allow them to view or comment on your work. Set the appropriate permissions and send the invitation.
Example Code in Google Colab
Here's a complete example of the steps described above:

# Install Pandas
!pip install pandas

# Import Pandas
import pandas as pd

# Create a simple DataFrame
data = {'Name': ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Charlie', 'David'],
        'Age': [24, 27, 22, 32],
        'City': ['New York', 'Los Angeles', 'Chicago', 'Houston']}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Display the DataFrame
print("DataFrame:")
print(df)

# Perform a basic operation: calculate the mean age
mean_age = df['Age'].mean()
print("\nMean Age:", mean_age)

# Import Matplotlib
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Plot the ages of individuals
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.bar(df['Name'], df['Age'], color='skyblue')
plt.xlabel('Name')
plt.ylabel('Age')
plt.title('Age of Individuals')
plt.show()
